{[%evp 0,25,38,36,38,-5,-8,-8,22,22,22,22,24,10,14,-27,-33,-72,-76,-105,-105,
-62,-37,-45,-47,-47,-47,-106]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3
b6 $6 {Black opts for a fianchetto in various line of the Nimzo Indian, but
this is certainly premature. Curiously, this move has been played by many
strong grandmasters, including Magsoodloo, Kovalev, Navara and others.} (5... d6
{This move is played with the intention to unblock the diagonal for the Bishop
on c8 with the move...e6-e5. On the other hand, it practically forces Black to
give the bishop pair and leave White's pawn centre stable.} 6. Nge2 e5 (6... c5
7. O-O Nc6 {was also tried by some strong players, but it leaves Black with a
problematic Bishop on c8.} 8. a3 Bxc3 ({After} 8... Ba5 9. Bc2 Qe7 10. b3 Bd7
11. Bb2 $14 {Black was very cramped in Ribes Peris, A - Predke, A La Roda 2019})
9. Nxc3 {Statically Black's position is awful, so he has to capture the d4
pawn.} cxd4 10. exd4 Nxd4 11. Bxh7+ Nxh7 12. Qxd4 $14 {Black has no
compensation for his weak Pawn on d6 and somewhat exposed king. Celsus,
P-Medeiros,J ICCF email 2019}) 7. O-O Re8 8. Qc2 c6 (8... Bxc3 9. Qxc3 e4 10.
Bc2 c6 11. Ng3 d5 12. f3 $36 {0-1 (29) Kristoferitsch, D (2306)-Nemeth, M (2446)
Graz 2022}) 9. a3 Ba5 10. b4 Bc7 11. Bb2 Nbd7 12. Rad1 Qe7 13. Ng3 Nf8 {
0-1 (43) Vera Gonzalez Quevedo,R (2544)-Kurajica,B (2548) Benidorm 2002 CBM
093 [Atlas,Valeri]} 14. Nce4 $1 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Be6 16. d5 $16) (5... Bxc3+ {
is a serious concession because Black mostly captures on c3 only after White
plays a2-a3.} 6. bxc3 d6 7. e4 e5 8. Ne2 c5 ({After} 8... Nc6 9. O-O Re8 10. f3
b6 11. Be3 Na5 12. Ng3 {Black found himself with no counterplay because the
c4-pawn can be easily protected with Qe2. On the other hand, White's
initiative on the kingside is developing itself. Speelman, J - Wells, I Brighton
1979}) 9. d5 Nh5 (9... Nbd7 10. f3 Ne8 11. g4 f6 12. Ng3 g6 13. h4 $16 {
1/2 (19) Stenborg,A-Liljedahl, L Bollnas 1973}) 10. h4 $1 (10. O-O Qf6 11. f4
Nxf4 12. Nxf4 exf4 13. Bxf4 Nd7 {Sarwinski,M (2345)-Adamski,J (2400) Jachranka
1987}) 10... Qf6 11. f3 Nf4 12. Bxf4 exf4 13. Qd2 $16) (5... Nc6 {is an
artificial attempt to make counterplay with e6-e5.} 6. Nge2 e5 (6... d5 {
leads to an inferior version of Carlsbad pawn structures because Black cannot
challenge the centre with c7-c5} 7. cxd5 exd5 8. a3 Bd6 9. Qc2 {White opts for
his usual setup, as in the main lines.} a6 10. f3 Re8 11. O-O $16 {Bluebaum, M
- Hansen,E Chess.com INT 2022}) 7. d5 Ne7 8. a3 {A well-timed move. Black
cannot retreat his bishop because it will be trapped after b2-b4.} Bxc3+ 9.
Nxc3 d6 10. O-O Ng6 11. f4 {White dominates on both sides of the board.
Karnkowski,A-Ziembinski,M Czestochowa 1956}) 6. e4 $1 {Both 6.Nf3 and 6.Nge2
are much more popular, but this is the most aggressive way to meet an early
fianchetto.} Bb7 {The most consistent.} ({The other continuations are:} 6... d5
7. cxd5 exd5 8. e5 Ne4 9. Nge2 {White has the benefit of connecting the
knights and keeping the f-pawn unblocked.} Bg4 ({Even worse is} 9... c5 $2 10.
O-O Bb7 11. a3 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Ba5 13. f4 $18 {White has a decisive positional
advantage: both Black's bishops are poor, and f4-f5 is to follow soon.}) 10.
Qc2 Bxe2 11. Kxe2 Bxc3 12. bxc3 $16 {White has both a dominant centre and two
powerful bishops. Georgiev,V - Dobrev,N Bansko 2010}) (6... c5 {, as in Sarana,
A - Kouskoutis, G Chess.com INT 2022 can be strongly met by} 7. e5 $1 $146 cxd4
({Equally bad is} 7... Ne8 8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Bb7 10. Nf3 $16) 8. a3 Bxc3+ 9.
bxc3 Ne8 10. cxd4 $16 {White takes a dominant centre, and his bishop pair
seems to play an important role in the long run.}) 7. Bg5 h6 8. h4 $1 {White
tactically defends his bishop, as in the Exchange variation of the Ruy Lopez
line starting with 5...Bg4 6.h3 h5. It turns out, that this pin is extremely
annoying for Black.} d6 ({The passive} 8... Be7 {also meets} 9. e5 Ne8 10. Qh5
Bxg5 11. hxg5 $18 {White's attack was crushing in Sarana, A - Dobrikov, M Chess.
com INT 2023}) ({Needless to say,} 8... hxg5 9. hxg5 g6 10. gxf6 Qxf6 11. Qd2 {
looks very bad for Black either.}) 9. e5 {A well-timed break! White joins his
bishop in attack with great effect.} dxe5 10. dxe5 Bxg2 {This position
occurred in David, A - Niezhentsev, K Bucharest 2023 White should have played} 11.
Rh2 $146 Be4 12. Rh3 $1 hxg5 13. hxg5 $18 {The consequences of opening h-file
seem fatal.} *

