{[%evp 0,31,18,15,18,18,18,18,23,20,20,20,56,44,35,35,46,29,27,27,54,46,35,-11,
-3,-34,4,-2,-2,14,31,40,48,46]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3
Re8 {This somewhat aritificial continuation is actually based on a healthy
positional idea: Black vacates the f8 square for his bishop and makes the
traditional exchange on d5 less attractive for White: Black's rook will be
well-placed on the semi-open file.} 6. Nge2 d5 7. O-O (7. cxd5 exd5 8. a3 Bf8 {
is something Black would be happy with: White's main plan with f2-f3 will be
not effective because Black is perfectly ready to meet it with c7-c5.}) 7...
Nbd7 {The most common move. Black waits until White plays a2-a3 to retreat the
bishop on f8. Also, in some cases, it is possible to unblock the Bc8 with ...
e6-e5.} (7... b6 {isn't well timed because White can exploit the temporary
weakness of long diagonal by means of} 8. e4 $1 dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nbd7 {This
position was reached in Kalogridis, A - Ioannidis, E Thessaloniki 2022} (9... Bb7
10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. Qc2 {is dangerous because White does threaten not only 12.
Bxh7+, but also 12.c5, almost trapping the Bb4.}) {Now White could have
claimed some drawback of Black's setup with} 10. Nxf6+ $146 Nxf6 11. c5 bxc5 {
This is forced in view of 12.a3, followed by b4.} 12. a3 c4 13. Bxh7+ $1 Nxh7
14. axb4 $14 {Black's pawn structure is more damaged the White's.}) (7... Bf8 {
is another natural try, but it doesn't follow the main rule: Black's
queenside pieces are still underdeveloped.} 8. Qc2 Nbd7 9. cxd5 {Switching to
''Carlsbad'' paths is a sensible choice because by putting the Knight on d7
Black doesn't really want to play c7-c5.} exd5 10. Kh1 $5 $146 {This flexible
continuation is a novelty. This king's move will be useful in case White plays
e3-e4 or g2-g4. Black is invited to show his cards.} ({After} 10. Bd2 c5 11.
dxc5 Nxc5 {Black had acceptable play in Aleksandrov, A - Kryakvin, D Loo 2013})
10... c5 {Black accepts an isolated pawn - in case of 11.dxc5 Nxc5 all his
queenside pieces will become active.} ({In case Black delays this break with} 
10... a6 {White can start attacking actions with} 11. Nf4 c6 12. f3 b5 13. g4
$1 $14 {with decent prospects on the kingside.}) 11. Nf4 $1 {White increases
his pressure on the d5 pawn.} cxd4 ({After} 11... c4 12. Be2 Nb6 13. f3 $14 {
the Knight on b6 is misplaced, and Black's further expansion with b7-b5 is
slowed down. At the same time, White is ready to push e3-e4.}) 12. exd4 Nb8 {
Black moves his knight towards c6, where it will be placed optimally. However,
this takes a lot of time.} 13. f3 Nc6 14. Qf2 $14 {Black still struggles to
develop his light-squared bishop, while White is ready to start his usual
activity with g2-g4.}) 8. Qc2 {I see no point rushing with the move a2-a3 -
the Bishop on b4 is actually misplaced. At the same time, White keeps an eye
on the h7 pawn and vacates the d1square for his rooks.} dxc4 ({In case of} 8...
c5 9. cxd5 exd5 10. a3 {White forces a favorable exchange.} Bxc3 11. Nxc3 c4
12. Be2 $14 {In the upcoming strategic struggle White's bishop pair will play
a key role. Black struggles to make further progress on the queenside because
White can always meet a7-a6 with the move a3-a4.}) ({Too passive is} 8... c6 9.
cxd5 exd5 10. f3 Nf8 11. Bd2 $14 {White has an improved version of the
mainlines because Black has already played the committing move c7-c6 and White
has saved a tempo on the movea2-a3. Next White will play the moves Rad1, Kh1
and then push e3-e4 at a proper moment. Milov,V - Javadov,R Baku 2008}) 9. Bxc4
c5 {Black challenges the centre in his attempt to claim the passive Ne2.} 10.
a3 {This is White's usual reaction to the move ...c7-c5 because Black cannot
retreat his bishop.} Bxc3 11. bxc3 Qc7 {Natural play by both sides has led to
this position in Lupulescu, C - Gukesh, D Zagreb 2023 Here I suggest the
following plan:} 12. Qa2 $5 $146 {White steps out of the pin and protects his
bishop. Next, he can either build a strong pawn centre with f2-f3 and e3-e4 or
opt for a3-a4 and place his bishop on a3.} a6 {This is the most challenging
reaction to White's original last move.} ({Worse is} 12... b6 $6 13. f3 Bb7 14.
e4 $16 {Black's pieces are well-restricted, so White has a huge positional
advantage.}) ({Insiffucient is also} 12... Nb6 13. Bb3 Bd7 14. a4 Nbd5 15. f3
$14 {White's central pawns become mobile.}) 13. Bd3 b5 14. e4 {Undoubtedly,
White's ability to play this move is a certain achievement as he claims the
centre.} e5 15. d5 c4 16. Bc2 $14 {Black doesn't have enough compensation for
White's strong free d5 pawn and also his strong bishop pair and stands worse.}
*

