{[%evp 0,37,19,19,27,17,1,13,19,19,17,17,17,2,54,55,57,13,13,-33,0,7,11,-6,-12,
-12,-12,-13,-16,-16,32,33,40,0,0,21,37,37,37,37]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 {This move is almost as frequent as the move 5...d5 in
practice. Black deviates from transposing to Carlsbad pawn structures, which
can be seen after 5...d5 6.cxd5.} 6. a3 {I like this aggressive choice. White
gains the bishop pair at the cost of some damage to his pawn structure - a
classical Nimzo-Indian type of scenario.} (6. Nge2 d5 7. cxd5 cxd4 8. exd4 Nxd5
{leads to long positional play with IQP. In my opinion, the modest placement
of Ne2 makes it difficult for White to claim superiority.}) 6... cxd4 {A solid
choice. Black avoids the closed type of positions that emerge after 6...Bxc3+
and opens the game.} 7. axb4 ({After} 7. exd4 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 d6 $132 {Black has
enough counterplay due to his development advantage and the weak white c4-pawn.
}) 7... dxc3 8. Ne2 $1 {This is the only way to fight for the initiative -
White is ready to sacrifice a pawn.} (8. bxc3 d6 $1 9. Nf3 e5 10. e4 Be6 11.
O-O Qc7 {was very comfortable for Black in Bocharov, D - Ponomariov, R Olginka
2011}) 8... d5 ({Risky is} 8... cxb2 9. Bxb2 d5 ({After} 9... b6 10. O-O Bb7
11. Ng3 {White has decent attacking prospects due to his active minor pieces.
For instance,} d5 12. cxd5 Qxd5 13. e4 Qg5 14. e5 Nd5 15. Ne4 {with a nearly
decisive advantage - White's knight will dominate because of the weakness of
the square d6.}) 10. c5 Nc6 (10... Re8 11. O-O e5 {, as in Swayams,M - Kunte,A
Mumbai 2010 can be strongly met by} 12. f4 $1 $146 Nc6 13. b5 e4 14. Bb1 $36 {
it will be very hard for Black to withstand such pressure on the long diagonal
- the White Bishop on b2 is just a monster!.}) 11. b5 Nb4 12. O-O Nxd3 13. Qxd3
$36 {Black is very cramped on the queenside, while his king is getting under
pressure along the a1-h8 diagonal.}) ({After} 8... Nc6 9. b5 Ne5 10. Nxc3 d5 {
the game might transpose to the text.}) 9. Nxc3 Nc6 {The most active response.}
(9... dxc4 {is a slight concession:} 10. Bxc4 Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 {the fact that
White cannot castle is not so important here.} Nc6 12. b5 Ne5 13. Be2 $14 {
White has both the bishop pair and pressure to the a7-pawn. Gurevich, D -
Pinter,J Helsinki 1983}) 10. b5 Ne5 (10... Nb4 11. O-O Nxd3 12. Qxd3 b6 {
took place in Huebner, R - Polugaevsky, L Tilburg 1985 White could have
benefited from having an unopposed dark-squared bishop with} 13. e4 $1 dxc4 14.
Qg3 Bb7 15. Rd1 $36 {The activity of White's pieces prevails - Black's minor
pieces are restricted by the White pawn on e4.}) 11. c5 $1 {Keeping the Black
Bishop on c8 out of play.} Nxd3+ ({Worth mentioning} 11... Nfd7 $5 12. b4 Qh4 {
, as was seen in a correspondence game. Here I suggest:} 13. e4 $5 $146 Ng4 ({
After} 13... dxe4 14. Be2 f5 15. O-O $16 {Black's queenside pieces are
cramped and his central pawn are immobile.}) 14. Ra2 {White has a huge
positional advantage, but some initiative is currently on Black's side.} d4 15.
g3 {it is essential to release pressure on f2.} Qf6 16. Na4 Nde5 17. f4 $1 {
White has to force the exchange of the active Black knight.} Nxd3+ 18. Qxd3 $14
{White's superior pawn piece coordination and pawn majority on the queenside
starts to tell.}) 12. Qxd3 e5 {Black's counter-play is based on his mobile
central pawns.} 13. O-O Be6 {Black aims to connect his rooks as soon as
possible.} ({Riskier is} 13... d4 $6 14. exd4 Qxd4 15. Qe3 $1 {A strong move.
White maintains all the merits of his position.} Rd8 {This was Sarana, A -
Carlsen, M Chess. com INT 2023 Now the energetic} 16. b6 $1 a6 17. Nb5 {would
have offered White a huge positional advantage,}) 14. Rd1 {White puts pressure
on the Black d5 pawn and makes it tougher for Black to advance it.} Qc7 (14...
Qd7 {doesn't really change very much:} 15. b4 Rfd8 16. Bb2 {White harmoniously
develops.} Bf5 {This was Tin, J - Svane, R Baku 2023 White could have claimed an
advantage by means of} 17. e4 $1 $146 dxe4 (17... Bxe4 18. Nxe4 Nxe4 19. Bxe5 {
is even worse for Black.}) 18. Qxd7 Bxd7 19. h3 h6 20. Rd6 $16 {Black's extra
pawn shouldn't be considered here - White dominates all the board.}) 15. b4 e4
{Black's only way to make counterplay is to attack the White h2 pawn.} 16. Qe2
Qe5 {we have been following Kalinitschew, S-Smagin, S Moscow 1982 In this
position, i would prefer for White} 17. Rd4 $146 Ng4 18. f4 {The only, but
sufficient defense.} exf3 19. gxf3 $36 {The White King's position isn't as
secured as before, but the strategic merits prevail: White can create a strong
passed pawn on the queenside, and the unopposed dark-squared bishop will be
much stronger than the Black Bishop on e6..} *

