always keep in his mind.} 11. Bc2 Bg4 ({After} 11... Na5 12. Ng3 Nxc4 13. Nxe4
$14 {White makes lots of progress by getting rid of weak Pc4 and activating
Bc2.}) 12. f3 {This break shouldn't be delayed, even though it somewhat
weakens White's king.} (12. Rxb7 Na5 13. Rb1 Nxc4 {is weaker because Black's
knight is getting very active.}) 12... exf3 13. gxf3 Bh3 14. Re1 $1 {A precise
retreat.} (14. Rf2 {allows} Nh5 $1 15. Rxb7 Qh4 {, and the Rf2 is mispalced -
White cannot move his king, and it puts it in potential danger on the g-file.})
14... Nh5 15. Kh1 {Now the king is relatively safe.} Qh4 16. Rg1 Na5 17. e4 {
The strong pawn centre is supported by bishops. Black has to deal with threats
such as 18.Bg5, and his position feels uncomfortable.}) (10... Re8 {Black
intents to play e5-e4 at the proper moment.} 11. Ng3 e4 {The only consistent
continuation.} ({In case of} 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 exd4 13. exd4 Nxd4 {the least
White can do is regaining the pawn in favorable situation:} 14. Bxh7+ Nxh7 15.
Qxd4 {White's pieces are more active, and also the Black d6 Pawn is weaker
than the White c4 Pawn.}) 12. Bc2 Bg4 {Black provokes f2-f3, though it is a
part of White's plan anyway.} 13. f3 exf3 14. gxf3 Bh3 15. Rf2 {White has
decent prospects in the centre, and the bishop pair should tell in the long
run. Soto Palomo,C - Lecha Gonzalez,J ICCF email 2008}) 11. Ng3 {I like this
flexible move. Hardly there is a better spot for the king's knight.} ({Another
interesting option is} 11. f3 $5 Re8 12. e4 {Black has to accept the pawn -
otherwise, Rf8-e8 turns a loss of time.} cxd4 13. cxd4 exd4 14. Bg5 Be6 15. f4
$44 {White's full compensation for a pawn is undeniable - it isn't easy for
Black to release the pressure along h4-d8 diagonal, and d4 is hard to protect.}
) 11... Re8 ({The attempt to stabilize the situation in the centre by means of
} 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 exd4 13. exd4 d5 {is wrong because it makes White's
bishops especially effective. Play could continue as follows:} 14. c5 $1 Nxd4
15. cxb6 axb6 16. Bxh7+ Kxh7 17. Qxd4 {White has a huge positional advantage
both because of safer king and superior pawn structure.}) 12. Bc2 $1 $146 {
This multi-tasking move is a novelty. White unblocks d-file for his queen and
prophylactically retreats his bishop in view of ...e5-e4. Also, Black has to
deal with ideas such as ..Bc2-a4.} (12. d5 {, as was seen in the preceding game
seems less promising in view of} e4 $1 13. Nxe4 Ne5 14. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $132 {
Black has an excellent piece play, and one of White's pawns should fall soon.})
12... exd4 $1 {A concrete approach - Black is aiming to stabilize the pawn
structure and secure the d5 square for his minor pieces.} ({After} 12... Na5
13. e4 $1 cxd4 14. cxd4 Nxc4 15. Qd3 Na5 16. f4 $36 {White's initiative
overwhelms a pawn - most of Black's pieces are far away from their King on g8,
so the upcoming White attack will be dangerous.}) 13. cxd4 cxd4 14. exd4 d5 {
Of course, Black was counting on this move.} 15. Bg5 {Among White's
possibilities this one seems to pose Black the biggest problems.} dxc4 {
Practically forced.} 16. Re1 $1 {White takes control over the open file.} (16.
d5 Ne5 17. Ne4 Bf5 {isn't so clear - Black can do with potential damage of
his pawn structure.}) 16... Rxe1+ 17. Qxe1 Bb7 18. Nf5 {White has excellent
play for the pawn. Black should be able to defend, but his task in a practical
game is difficult.} *

