{[%evp 0,27,19,25,27,17,1,20,19,17,19,17,25,25,40,48,54,41,39,42,42,39,39,34,
34,26,26,37,43,46]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. cxd5
Qxd5 {This somewhat provocative move is connected with the idea of exchanging
the problematic Black light-squared bishop with ...b7-b6 and Bc8-a6.} (6...
Nxd5 {is often played with similar ideas to 6...Qxd5, but it diminishes
Black's control over the e4.square.} 7. Nge2 c5 ({Too risky is} 7... b6 8. e4
Nxc3 9. bxc3 Be7 {White has a stable centre, and he can quickly develop a
powerful attack with} 10. e5 $1 Bb7 11. Nf4 $40 {Black is missing some
defenders around his monarch.}) 8. a3 {The most forcing continuation.} ({
Instead,} 8. O-O cxd4 9. exd4 {might transpose to the tabiya, that arises often
after 5...c5.}) 8... Ba5 ({After} 8... cxd4 9. axb4 dxc3 10. bxc3 {White has
all the chances to activate both of his bishops because e3-e4 is on the way.}
Nc6 11. O-O Ne5 12. Bc2 $14 {Black still struggles to develop his bishop,
while White is ready to expand with e3-e4 and f2-f4. Gurevich,D - Buchenau,F
Chess.com INT 2021}) ({Another option is} 8... Bxc3+ {, but it is a certain
concession because White has both his powerful bishops and superiority in
the centre.} 9. bxc3 b6 10. O-O Ba6 {This is the only adequate attempt to
justify 8...Bxc3 - Black is interested in exchanging the active white bishop on
d3.} ({Too passive is} 10... Bb7 11. e4 Nf6 12. f3 {Dokutchaev,A - Klientov,V
Kaluga 1996}) 11. e4 Ne7 12. h4 $5 {I like this aggressive idea - White not
only puts opponent's king under some pressure in view of ..h4-h5-h6, but also
cuts g6 from Black's knight.} Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nbc6 14. h5 $14 {Black's position
feels rather cramped in view of his passive Knight on e7.}) 9. O-O cxd4 10.
Nxd5 $5 {10.exd4 was played by a few strong players, including Carlsen.
However, I would like to stick to this forcing move.} Qxd5 ({In case of} 10...
exd5 11. Nxd4 Nc6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Qc2 $14 {Black suffers from the vulnerablity
of the pawns on c6 and h7.}) 11. Qc2 $1 {Before capturing on d4 White gains an important
tempo by attacking the Black Pawn on h7.} h6 12. Nxd4 $14 {This position with
a symmetrical pawn structure is quite unpleasant for Black because his
queenside pieces are still undeveloped.}) 7. Nf3 b6 8. Qe2 $1 {This precie
move is a novelty. White not only prepares traditional expansion in the centre
with e3-e4, but also prevents ...Ba6.} ({Instead, after} 8. O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3
Ba6 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 {Black was able to swap the bishops and obtain a solid
position in Wojtaszek,R - Tiviakov,S Wroclaw 2010}) 8... Bb7 ({In case Black
insists to exchange the bishops and plays} 8... Qa5 9. Bd2 Ba6 {White can
liquidate into a comfortable endgame with} 10. Bxa6 Qxa6 11. Qxa6 Nxa6 12. Ke2
c5 13. Rac1 $14 {White's pieces are better mobilized, and the poor Knight on
a6 causes Black definite problems.}) 9. O-O {Black's queen is already attacked,
so White saves a tempo by omitting the move a2-a3.} Bxc3 10. bxc3 Nbd7 {
Black has control over the long diagonal and his pieces are harmoniously
placed.} 11. c4 Qh5 12. Nd2 {White invites favorable simplifications in order
to release the pressure on his king created by the active Black pieces.} Qxe2
13. Bxe2 c5 14. a4 $14 {There is not enough pressure on White's pawn centre.
White bishop pair will support the thematic a4-a5 advance and therefore White
stands slightly better.} *

