{[%evp 0,41,18,15,18,18,18,18,23,20,20,22,20,21,21,-5,3,3,3,-8,-4,-12,-10,-11,
-11,-32,-20,-6,-10,-10,-8,-27,-14,-16,-4,0,-13,-27,0,-19,0,0,-2,0]} 1. d4 Nf6
2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. a3 Bxc3+ {This is the
most natural reation to White's 7.a3 - Black doesn't wish to waste a tempo in
order to retreat his bishop. On the downside, it is a committing decision:
Black gives the bishop pair and strenghtens d4, so potentially White can
create at some point a strong pawn centre with e3-e4.} 8. bxc3 c5 {This
important position can be reached by different move orders. For instance,
White can start with 4.a3 or 4.e3 0-0 5.a3, and then Black captures on c3 and
plays d7-d5,c7-c5.} 9. Ne2 b6 {Black's bishop is problematic in such positions
- there is nothing to do on the c8-h3 diagonal. Therefore, he chooses to
exchange him by playing b6 and Ba6.} (9... Nc6 10. f3 Re8 11. O-O {was seen in
many games. There are many strong players who have taken Black's side,
including Fabiano Caruana. Still, this position can hardly be considered
accpetable for the second player. For instance,} Bd7 ({After} 11... c4 12. Bc2
b5 13. Ng3 a5 14. e4 $16 {White's initiative is lasting itself.}) 12. Nf4 {
For some reason, this natural move is practically untested. Black suffers from
White's pressure on d5, and g2-g4 might be annoying.} (12. Ng3 $5 Rc8 13. Rb1
Qc7 14. Qd2 {as in Thingstad,E - Urkedal,F Norway 2012 also looks promisin for
White. Next, he will mobilze his forces with Bb2, Rae1.}) 12... Rc8 13. g4 h6
14. Ra2 $36 {White had excellent attacking prospects in Rudolph,J -
Nonnenmacher,E Baden 1995}) (9... Bg4 {is another way to solve the issue of
the passive Black bishop} 10. f3 Bh5 11. Nf4 Bg6 12. Be2 $1 {A decent idea -
the Bishop on g6 is actually misplaced, so White can either capture it or try
to trap him by means of h4-h5.} ({Instead, the routine} 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. O-O
Nc6 14. Ra2 Re8 {was solid for Black in Potkin,V - Alekseev,E St Petersburg})
12... Nc6 ({After} 12... Qc7 13. g4 $1 Rd8 14. g5 Nh5 (14... Ne8 15. h4 $16)
15. Nxg6 hxg6 16. f4 $16 {The Knight on h5 will stay out of play untill the
end of the game.}) 13. h4 h5 {We have been following the game Bacrot,E -
Vallejo Pons,F Morelia/Linares 2006 A natural follow up could be} 14. Nxg6 $146
fxg6 15. O-O Ne7 16. Bd3 Qc7 17. a4 $14 {A long positional struggle is ahead,
but White is on top because of his bishop pair and the weak black pawn on g6.})
(9... Re8 10. O-O Bg4 {This is a rare continuation - Black is aiming to
transfer his bishop to g6 so as to exchange him with the White Bishop.} 11. f3
Bh5 12. dxc5 $5 {I like this sudden change of plans - it isn't about winning a
pawn, but mostly opening the game.} Nbd7 13. Bb5 {It turns out, that Rf8-e8
has some drawbacks as well!} Rc8 14. c4 $1 dxc4 ({Worse is} 14... Rxc5 $2 15.
Bb2 {with a threat of ..Bxf6.}) 15. c6 bxc6 16. Bxc4 $14 {White has both a
superior pawn structure and two powerful bishops.}) 10. O-O Ba6 ({Sometimes
Black delays Bc8-a6 with} 10... Re8 {, but it can be also met with:} 11. dxc5
bxc5 12. c4 Ba6 {There is nothing better} 13. cxd5 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 Qxd5 15. Qc2 {
The most promising - White can gain some tempi by attacking the Black Queen on
d5.} Nbd7 ({After} 15... Rd8 16. Ng3 Nc6 17. Bb2 $14 {White's bishop feels
very strong.}) 16. Rd1 Qe4 17. Qxe4 Rxe4 18. Rb1 Nb6 {This positon occured in
Georgiev,V - Drenchev,P Skopje 2011 Here I mostly like} 19. f3 $146 Rc4 20. e4
Rc2 21. Ng3 $14 {The active Black Rook on c2 doesn't provide Black with full
compensation for his weak Pawn on c5 and White's control over the d-file.}) 11.
Bxa6 {A positional approach. White is interested in getting a rid of weak Pc3
and activating his bishop.} ({The mainline starts with} 11. f3 Re8 12. Ng3 Bxd3
13. Qxd3 Nc6 14. Bb2 {White scores well on practice, but after} h5 $1 $132 {
Black seems to have adequate counterplay due to h5-h4 resourse.}) 11... Nxa6
12. Qd3 {Attacking the knight and getting ready for ..c3-c4.} Nc7 {The top
choice by far.} ({Strategically bad is} 12... c4 $6 13. Qc2 b5 14. f3 Re8 15.
Ng3 $16 {White's play in the centre with e3-e4 prevails.}) (12... Qc8 {is
somewhat awkward, although Black temporarily prevents c3-c4. White naturally
continues with} 13. f3 Re8 14. Ng3 Qb7 15. Bd2 {A simple idea - White connects
his rooks and prepares ..Rae1 and e3-e4.} Re6 16. Rae1 Rae8 {Black mobilizes
all his forces to stop e3-e4, but now another break is possible.} 17. Nf5 Nc7
18. c4 $1 {White was much more active in Narkun,M - Pech,S LSS email 2015}) (
12... Nb8 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. c4 dxc4 15. Qxc4 Nbd7 16. e4 Qb6 17. f3 $14 {
Tabatabaei,M - Yuffa,D Sharjah 2023}) 13. dxc5 $1 {White favorably changes the
pawn structure and activates his bishop.} bxc5 14. c4 Rb8 ({The alternative is
} 14... dxc4 15. Qxc4 Qd5 (15... Ne6 16. Bb2 Qd5 17. Qc2 Qe4 18. Rfc1 Qxc2 19.
Rxc2 $14 {was better for White in Melkumyan,H - Gharibyan,M Yerevan 2018}) 16.
Qxd5 Ncxd5 17. f3 {White pawns duo on f3 and e4 will restrict Black's knights.}
Nb6 ({Or} 17... Rfc8 18. e4 Ne7 19. Be3 $14 {Petrosyan,M -Tsydypov,Z Lichess.
org INT 2021}) 18. e4 Na4 {Natural play by both sides has led to this position
in Melkumyan,H - Abasov,N Jerusalem 2015 Now I suggest the following natural
way of handling this endgame:} 19. Rd1 $146 Rfd8 20. Bf4 h6 21. Rab1 $14 {
Black is doomed to passive defence.}) 15. Rd1 $1 {A strong move. White takes
control over the open file.} (15. cxd5 Qxd5 16. Qxd5 Ncxd5 {offers Black an
improved version of endgame because his knights are active.}) 15... dxc4 ({
After} 15... Qe7 16. Bd2 dxc4 17. Qxc4 Ncd5 18. Rac1 $14 {White's positional
advantage was undeniable in Kramnik,V - Inarkiev,E Krasnogorsk 2022}) 16. Qc2
Qe7 17. Qxc4 Rfd8 {Both sides have optimally placed their forces.} 18. Bd2 Ne6
{This position was reached in Ghysens,D - Schmidt,T ICCF email 2020 White has
a quite a few interesting possibilities, but I prefer:} 19. Nc3 $146 h6 20. Be1
Qc7 21. h3 $14 {Black has no compensation for his inferior pawn structure.
Undoubtedly, the Black c5 pawn is weak in this position and Black has to take
care of it. Therefore he stands slightly worse.} *

