{[%evp 0,27,18,15,18,18,10,10,23,20,23,22,17,17,22,-5,27,31,49,28,49,49,39,32,
32,1,33,31,17,17]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. cxd5
exd5 7. a3 Be7 {A relatively rare move. At the same time, it has to be
mentioned that the current position is often reached with 6.a3 Be7 7.cxd5 exd5.
} 8. Nge2 {In most cases, White chooses to leave the f2 Pawn unblocked for
further actions on the kingside.} b6 {This is the most logical follow-up:
Since Black has better control of the d-file in comparison to 7...Bd6, his
active plan starting with b7-b6 and c7-c5 makes sense now.} ({The other
possibilities are:} 8... c6 9. O-O Re8 10. Bd2 {White completes development
and connects his rooks before committing himself to f2-f3.} Nbd7 (10... a5 {
, as in Hakobyan,A - Suleymanli,A Chess.com INT 2023 has usual drawback - it
makes it much more problematic to meet f2-f3 with c6-c5, so after} 11. f3 $1 c5
12. Be1 cxd4 13. exd4 Nc6 14. Bh4 {White obtains an excellent position with a
slight, but long-lasting advantage: Black suffers from weak b5-spot, and his
pieces are placed less harmoniously.}) 11. Qc2 b6 ({After} 11... a5 12. f3 $1
c5 13. Bb5 $14 {Black's setup looks awkward.}) 12. e4 $1 {A well-timed break.
White takes his oppostunity of opening the diagonal before Black puts his
Bishop on b7.} dxe4 13. Nxe4 Bb7 {It isn't a standard IQP because the Pawns on
d4 and c6 are equally weak.} 14. Ng5 $1 {White avoids unnecesary
simplifications.} Nf8 15. Bc4 Nd5 16. Nf3 {White keeps some pressure due to
his more active pieces.}) ({and} 8... Re8 9. O-O Nbd7 10. b4 {White grabs
space and makes it no possible to play ...c7-c5.} a5 {This was Von Wersch,O -
Buydts, D IECG email 1996 The natural follow-up of White's strategy would be}
11. Rb1 $146 axb4 12. axb4 c6 13. f3 $14 {The further .. e3-e4 looks promising,
while Black's counterplay is problematic.}) 9. O-O c5 {The most consistent.
Black doesn't mind to play with ''hanging pawns'' after possible 10.dxc5 bxc5.}
(9... Bb7 {is met by} 10. b4 $1 {, heavily limiting Black's counter-attacking
abiltiies} Nbd7 (10... Re8 11. Rb1 Bd6 12. f3 $14 {is about the same - Black
lacks any constructive ideas, while e3-e4 is in the air.}) 11. Rb1 {I like
this prophylactic move. White radically prevents ... c7-c5 as the Bb7 will be
hanging.} (11. Qb3 $5 {is a similar idea that scores well on practice.}) 11...
Re8 12. f3 $1 $146 {The key e3-e4 advance in Carlsbad type of positions is
always effective when Black can't play ...c7-c5.} ({Instead,} 12. b5 a6 13. a4
axb5 14. axb5 Bd6 {provided Black some counter-play in Rakhmanov,A - Bocharov,
D Serpukhov 2018}) 12... Bf8 13. Qc2 $36 {Both ...e3-e4 and g2-g4 look
dangerous for Black.}) (9... Ba6 {weakens the light squares} 10. Nf4 Bxd3 11.
Qxd3 Qd7 ({After} 11... c6 12. f3 Nbd7 13. Rd1 $14 {White will choose a proper
moment for taking the upper hand in centre with e3-e4.}) 12. Bd2 Nc6 {The
natural play by both sides led to this position in Schmidek,E - Naiditsch,A
Karlsruhe 2020 In my opinion, the best way of claiming drawbacks of 9...Ba6 was
} 13. Qb5 $1 a6 14. Qa4 Rfd8 15. Rac1 $14 {Black is under strong pressure on
the queenside.}) 10. Nf4 {A reasonable choice - there is no need to capture
on c5 that will make Black's central pawns mobile. Instead, White activates
his knight and insists pressure on d5.} Bb7 11. Qf3 {The pin makes it no
possible for Black to play c5-c4. Also, he has some issues with the Knight on
b8.} Na6 {Black finally completes his development, but this meets with a
concrete reaction from White's side.} ({After} 11... Qd7 12. Rd1 {Black can
release the tension with} c4 13. Bc2 b5 {, but this can backfire: White feels
ready to act aggressively on the king- side.} 14. g4 $1 g6 {This was Duong,T -
Dang,A Tinh Bac Giang 2022 White should have continued his main strategy
starting with:} 15. g5 $146 Ne4 16. Ncxd5 $1 Nxg5 17. Qg2 $36 {White's
superiority in the centre prevails. Black's king will likely get under attack
soon.}) 12. Bxa6 $1 Bxa6 13. Rd1 {The opposition on the d-file is quite
annoying for Black.} cxd4 14. Rxd4 $14 {Black has no adequate compensation for
his weak isolated pawn. Nevole,M - Vondracek,E ICCF email 2003} *

