{[%evp 0,35,18,15,11,15,15,19,24,20,22,22,21,21,13,-5,21,-4,-4,4,-6,-4,10,2,20,
14,20,-9,9,9,8,-12,-18,-21,-4,-28,-4,-28]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3
O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. a3 Bd6 8. Qc2 {An accurate move. White not only
threatens to exchange the powerful bishop of opponent with 9.Nb5, but also
diminshes the effect of ...c7-c5 because it will make the Bishop on c5
vulnerable.} b6 {The main point of this move isn't to fianchetto the c8 Bishop,
but to prepare the move...c7-c5.} (8... Re8 {ignores White's main strategic
idea.} 9. Nb5 $1 {Exchanging the strong bishop is a certain achievement.} Nc6
10. Nxd6 Qxd6 11. Ne2 a5 12. f3 $14 {Black is missing his bishop, and the Nc6
is mispalced as well. Kashlinskaya,A - Kosteniuk,A Germany 2022}) (8... c5 {
Among Black's minor possibilities this is the most challenging move - White's
kingside isn't developed yet, so Black signals that he will try to open the game
with further ...d5-d4.} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Nf3 $1 {This way of development
should be prefered because White takes control of both d4 and e5.} (10. Nge2
Nc6 11. O-O Ne5 {looks fine for Black.}) 10... Nc6 (10... Re8 11. O-O Bg4 {
, as in Checa,N -Yoo,C Saint Louis 2022 can be met by} 12. Ng5 $5 {White
invites interesting complications.} h6 13. Nxf7 Kxf7 14. Nxd5 $1 {This
beautiful tactical shot allows White to regain material.} Nxd5 ({Hardly more
attractive for Black is} 14... Nbd7 15. Bg6+ Kg8 16. Bxe8 Nxe8 17. Bd2 $14) 15.
Bg6+ Kg8 16. Bxe8 Qxe8 17. Qxc5 $14 {The rook with pawns overwhelm Black's
minor pieces because White can quickly advance the e-pawn and activate his
rooks.}) 11. O-O Bg4 12. Ng5 $1 {White has to avoid the damage of his pawn
chain with ...Bxf3.} h6 13. Nh7 Nxh7 14. Bxh7+ Kh8 15. Bf5 {This move is very
important because White neutralizes Black's temporary activity.} Bh5 16. Ne2 $1
{A strong move. White not only attacks the bishop, but also decalres his
intent to play ..Nf4.} Bxe2 17. Qxe2 d4 {This is the only challenging option -
statically Black is worse.} 18. Bb1 $1 {What a spectacular idea! Almost all
White's pieces are at backrank, but they are effective!} Qe7 19. b4 Bb6 20. b5
$1 {A concrete approach - Before capturing d4 White has to move opponent's
knight.} Ne5 (20... dxe3 $2 21. Qc2 exf2+ 22. Kh1 {leads to material losses.})
21. exd4 Bxd4 22. Ra2 $14 {White is better due to his powerful bishops.}) (8...
a5 {also meets} 9. Nb5 b6 10. Ne2 {White can capture d6 at any moment.} Ba6 11.
Bd2 c6 12. Nxd6 Qxd6 13. O-O $14 {White can both press on the c-file and
prepare e3-e4. Sargissian,G - Beliavsky,A Terme Catez 2022}) 9. Nb5 c5 10. b3
$1 {White keeps the tension and prevents the nasty ...c5-c4.} ({Worse is} 10.
Nxd6 $6 Qxd6 11. Ne2 {Kobo,O - Sarana,A Chess.com INT 2022} c4 12. Bf5 Nc6 $15)
10... Be7 ({The more active} 10... Nc6 {allows White to capture the bishop} 11.
Nxd6 Qxd6 12. Ne2 {White's main task at this point is completing development
without serious concessions.} cxd4 13. exd4 Bg4 {Black bases his counterplay
on active piece play.} 14. f3 Bh5 15. Bf4 Qe6 16. Qd2 $1 {the queen has to be
moved from potential opposition with Rc8.} Bg6 17. Ba6 $14 {White has a
superior piece coordination. The strong White Bishop on a6 makes it difficult
for Black to fight for the control of the open c-file.}) 11. Nf3 a6 12. Nc3 {
The knight has performed his job and returns back.} Bb7 13. O-O Nbd7 {Both
sides naturally develop their pieces.} 14. Bb2 {A standard position with
hanging pawn has been reached. A likely continuation could be:} Rc8 (14... Re8
15. Rfd1 Bd6 16. Bf5 {looks perfectly playable, but Black still has to solve
some issues with the weak Pawn on d5.}) 15. Qe2 b5 16. dxc5 {it is a good
moment to capture on c5 - otherwise Black will expand with c5-c4.} Nxc5 17. Bf5
Rc7 18. Nd4 $14 {White has a comfortable play against Black's isolated pawn on
d5. Gomez Esteban,J - Giorgadze,G Mondariz 1999} *

