{[%evp 0,37,18,15,18,18,18,18,23,19,20,20,20,21,21,-3,22,11,13,14,24,13,14,23,
4,-15,-14,3,-13,-24,-27,-18,-17,-19,-14,-12,22,29,7,9]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. a3 Bd6 8. Qc2 c6 9. Nge2 Re8 10.
Bd2 Na6 (10... Bg4 $6 {Black is trying to solve the issue with the passive
Bishop on c8 without weakening his queenside with b7-b6} 11. f3 Bh5 12. O-O-O
{Black is far from making serious threats on the queenside, so this is a safe
decision.} b5 13. e4 dxe4 14. fxe4 $16 {White was much better due to his
strong pawn centre. Urh,Z - Berke,A Chennai 2022}) (10... b5 {initiates a
risky plan Black intents to exhanhe the bishops with a7-a5, Ba6, but this
drastically weakens the pawn on c6.} 11. f3 a5 ({Worse is} 11... a6 $6 12. g4
$1 c5 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. g5 {Black was on the verge of collapse in Predke,A -
Gimenez Aguirre,I Chess.com INT 2023}) 12. O-O Ba6 13. Nd1 $1 {White moves his
knight towards d3 and unblocks the file.} b4 14. axb4 axb4 15. Nf2 $14 {
Black has no compensation for his structural drawbacks.}) (10... a5 {Black
makes it tougher for White to go for a minority attack with b2-b4 and vacates
the a6 square for his knight.} 11. O-O Na6 ({Inconsistent is} 11... Nbd7 12. f3
c5 13. Bb5 Qb6 14. Rac1 $16 {Black lacks harmony in his position and his pawn
on d5 is especially weak. Launhardt,W - Kepinski,J LSS email 2012}) 12. Rad1
Nc7 {The most logical follow-up. We have been following the game Bluebaum,M -
Sjugirov,S Chess.com INT 2022} ({Weaker is} 12... Qc7 13. h3 Bd7 {Black's
knight is stuck on a6 in the game Aleksandrov,A - Baskin,R Lichess.org INT
2020 White could have claimed superiority with the energetic:} 14. e4 $1 dxe4
15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 h6 17. Rfe1 $14 {Neutralizing the activity of White's
pieces isn't an easy task.}) {Here I suggest} 13. f3 $146 c5 {Black should
play this move, as usual.} 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Nd4 Ne6 {Black keeps fighting for
the control of the d4 square.} ({Something timid like} 15... h6 {is met by} 16.
Na4 $1 Ba7 17. Nc5 $14 {leaves Black in unpleasant situation, when his bishop
is undeveloped and a5 is weak.}) 16. Kh1 $1 {A temporary pawn sacrfiice.
White's play is based on the promising opposition on the d-file.} Bxd4 ({
The other capture is weaker:} 16... Nxd4 17. exd4 Bxd4 18. Bg5 $36 {White will
regain the pawn and will keep the pressure.}) 17. exd4 Nxd4 18. Qb1 h6 ({
Also after} 18... Be6 19. Bg5 h6 20. Bh4 Nc6 21. Qc1 {White has excellent play
for a pawn becuase Black struggles to avoid the pin, and f4-f5 might be very
annoying.}) 19. Be1 Nc6 20. Bh4 $44 {White has good compensation for the pawn:
His pieces are better coordinated and Black has no good way to step out of the
pin along the h4-d8 diagonal.}) 11. O-O ({Somewhat premature is} 11. f3 c5 12.
g4 c4 13. Bf5 Bxf5 14. Qxf5 Nc7 {Black had excellent play in Predke,A -
Firouzja,A Warsaw 2021}) 11... Nc7 12. b4 ({After} 12. f3 c5 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14.
Nd4 Ne6 {chances were rougly equal in Mirzoev,E - Papadopoulos,I Gladenbach
2022}) 12... Ne6 ({Worthy of serious attention is:} 12... a5 $5 {, although
after} 13. b5 cxb5 14. Nxb5 Nxb5 15. Bxb5 {Black's pawn structure isn't
perfect. A likely continuation would be} Bd7 16. Rfb1 Rc8 17. Qd3 {This is
acceptable according to the engines, but Black has still to prove, that he has
enough compensation for his weak queenside pawns.}) 13. f3 a5 (13... Bc7 {
with the intention to attack the pawn on h2 is met with:} 14. Be1 $1 Ng5 15.
Bf2 Qd6 16. Ng3 {It is only a matter of time before White will take the upper
hand in the centre with e3-e4. Aleksandrov,A - Firouzja,M Europe Echecs INT
2020}) 14. bxa5 Rxa5 15. a4 {Technically speaking, White's a4 pawn is a
wekaness. On the other hand, it is well-protected by his pieces, while Black's
pieces will be tied to the defence of the b7 pawn.} Ra7 16. Kh1 Bb8 {Natural
play by both sides las led to the current position in Lazavik,D - Wagner,D
Chess.com INT 2022 In my opinion, White should have neutralized Black's
counterplay against the h2 pawn starting with:} 17. Be1 $146 Nf8 18. Bf2 Ng6
19. Rab1 $14 {Black's play is difficult as he has to watch out for both White
pawn pushes: e3-e4 and g2-g4. Furthermore, his position is passive.} *

