{[%evp 0,41,19,19,27,15,19,19,25,27,27,22,22,12,26,-10,24,5,23,21,16,23,24,17,
17,6,17,0,0,-3,5,-12,-16,-16,-4,-4,-15,-18,-17,-17,-19,-19,-19,0]} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. a3 Bd6 8. Qc2 c6 9. Nge2
Re8 10. Bd2 b6 {Another serious possibility, that was recently tested on the
highest level. It's main point is Black's ability to recapture bxc5 after ...
c6-c5.} 11. f3 {A well-timed move. White keeps both options of e3-e4 and g2-g4
available, while his king can be placed on the queenside in some cases.} ({
After} 11. O-O c5 $1 {Black has nothing to worry about.}) 11... c5 {The most
logical follow-up of 10...b6 - Black is aiming to open file against opponent's
king.} ({A sensible choice is also} 11... Ba6 $5 12. g4 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nbd7 {
The most natural developing move. The only downside is that Black cannot
retreat his other knight to d7.} ({Premature is} 13... c5 $6 14. g5 Nfd7 15.
Qf5 cxd4 16. exd4 $16 {The Pawn on d5 is about to fall. Siddharth, J - Shmeliov,
D Charlotte 2022}) 14. g5 Nh5 15. e4 {White decides to extend in the centre,
even though his king is still in the centre.} c5 (15... dxe4 16. fxe4 c5 17.
O-O-O {is another possible move order.}) 16. O-O-O {There will be no other
good moment to play this move!} dxe4 17. fxe4 cxd4 18. Nxd4 Be5 ({After} 18...
Bf8 $5 19. Qe3 Ne5 20. Rhf1 {the chances are roughly equal, but the ball is on
Black's court!}) 19. Nc6 Qc8 ({The natural} 19... Qc7 $6 {is inaccurate on
account of} 20. Nxe5 Nxe5 21. Qe2 g6 22. Kb1 $36 {Black suffers from weak dark
squares around his king.}) 20. Nxe5 Nxe5 21. Qc2 {In this complex position
White's practical task seems somewhat easier because of the passive h5 Black
Knight.}) 12. g4 $1 {There is no way back! After this move, both sides play
''All in'' more or less!} c4 {Black builds his counterplay on pawn majority.} (
12... Nc6 {is another very natural move that wasn't tested yet} 13. g5 cxd4 {
invites interesting complications.} 14. Nb5 $1 ({Instead,} 14. gxf6 Qxf6 15.
Nb5 dxe3 16. Bc3 Qh4+ 17. Kd1 Be5 {provides Black plenty of play for the piece.
}) 14... dxe3 15. Qxc6 exd2+ 16. Kxd2 {An exciting situation! 3 Black's pieces
are hanging, but White's king is unsafe. Therefore, we should keep analyzing!}
Bc5 17. Qxa8 Ne4+ $1 {Black plays creatively and certainly puts pressure on
White's king.} 18. fxe4 dxe4 19. Nf4 {The only defence but a sufficient. one.}
Qxg5 20. Bc4 Qxf4+ 21. Kc2 {White has good chances for converting his material
advantage.}) (12... g6 $6 {threatens to trap the bishop, but after} 13. Bb5 $1
Bd7 14. Bxd7 Nbxd7 15. O-O-O {White achieves a harmonious setup when the d5
Pawn is very vulnerable and the g6-pawn turns out to be a target after..
h4-h5-h6.}) 13. Bf5 Bxf5 14. Qxf5 g6 {it is essential to release the pressure
on d5.} 15. Qc2 $5 $146 {I like this new idea. White prefers not to block the
g-file with his queen.} (15. Qg5 Nc6 16. O-O Bf8 17. Qh4 h6 18. Rad1 b5 $132 {
was unclear in Firouzja, A - Dominguez Perez, L Bucharest 2022}) 15... Nc6 16. h4
{White signals that he will open the files against Black's king very soon.} Na5
{Black transfers his knight to b3...a-la Botvinnik - Capablanca!} ({After} 
16... a6 {it makes sense for White to keep his king on f2:} 17. Kf2 $1 b5 18.
g5 Nh5 {The knight is doing a great job by blocking the h-file, but the
central pawn falls.} 19. Nxd5 Bxa3 20. e4 {White has a promising setup when
his king is relatively safe and next he can challenge the opponent's pawn chain
with b2-b3.}) ({A similar try is} 16... Rb8 17. Kf2 b5 18. g5 b4 {The most
aggressive!} 19. gxf6 bxc3 20. Nxc3 {This position looks scary for a second
player: White's attacking plan includes Rag1, h5, e.t. c.}) 17. g5 Nb3 (17...
Nh5 18. Nxd5 Nb3 19. Kf2 {leads to the same position.}) 18. Kf2 $1 {it turns
out, that White can leave the rook hanging!} ({Instead, the timid} 18. Rd1 Nh5
19. Nxd5 {meets} Nxd4 $1 20. Nxd4 Bg3+ 21. Kf1 Qxd5 {, and Black is on top.})
18... Nxa1 19. Rxa1 Nh5 20. Nxd5 b5 (20... Bxa3 21. e4 Bd6 22. Qxc4 {seems to
be more problematic for Black.}) 21. e4 $44 {Creating a dominant centre. White
is now ready to continue with the moves Ne3,Bc3, d5 and has a very pleasant
position.} *

