Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. a3 Bd6 8. Qc2 c6 9. Nge2 Re8 10. Bd2
Nbd7 {A flexible continuation. Black keeps his pawn structure compact. Later
he will make a decision about the fianchetto of his Bishop. In some cases
Black can also play ...Nf8-g6 and place the Knight on e6.} 11. f3 (11. O-O b6
12. Ng3 c5 13. e4 Bxg3 14. fxg3 c4 {Shankland, S - Keymer, V Prague 2023}) 11...
c5 {This is the most common and typical reaction to f2-f3 in such positions.} ({
A reasonable alternative is} 11... Nf8 12. O-O ({Too risky is} 12. O-O-O $6 b5
13. e4 b4 $15 {So, W - Anand, V Warsaw 2022}) 12... c5 {This reaction is
definitely critical - Black shouldn't allow White to build a strong pawn
centre with e3-e4.} ({There are a few other options:} 12... Qc7 {, as in So, W
