$36 {White can do with weakening g3, while Black suffers from lack of harmony.}
) (12... Bc7 {Sasikiran,K - Roulet Dubonnet,E Fagernes 2022} 13. Kh1 $1 Qd6 14.
g3 {Black managed to provoke g2-g3, but it doesn't really bother White as his
king remains safe. At the same time, Black's setup isn't optimal because e4-e5
break is in the air now.} Bh3 15. Rf2 h5 16. Rg1 $14 {Black lacks any
constructive counterplay, when White is planning e3-e4 or even g3-g4 at some
point.}) (12... Ng6 {Deuer, M - Heimisson, H Prague 2023 is hardly a sensible
idea as the Ng6 isn't effective} 13. Kh1 $1 {A universal prophylactic move.} Be6
14. Rad1 Qc7 15. Be1 $1 {Undirectly covering h2 and intending to complete an
optimal setup with 16.Bf2, followed by e3-e4.}) 13. Rad1 Ne6 ({After} 13... a6
14. Kh1 $1 Ne6 15. Be1 cxd4 16. exd4 $14 {The symmetric pawn structure doesn't
ease Black's play - White has a superior pawn structure, and Be1-h4 will
follow soon.}) 14. Be1 cxd4 ({Releasing the tension with} 14... c4 15. Bf5 {
is too risky:} g6 16. Bxe6 Bxe6 17. Bh4 $36 {White's initiative on the kingside
prevails.}) 15. exd4 Qc7 {So far both sides played naturally in Koneru, H - Tan,
Z Dubai 2023 White should have ignored Black's last move with} 16. Bh4 $1 $146
Bxh2+ 17. Kh1 {The threat of 18.Bxf6 is hard to parry.} g5 18. Qc1 $1 h6 ({
White's attack is equally strong after} 18... gxh4 19. Qh6 $40) 19. g3 gxh4 20.
Qxh6 $40 {Black's king feels very exposed.}) 12. h4 $1 {It turns out, that
White will not necessarily opt for a short castle! The last move declares
White's intention to play g2-g4-g5 and attack both d5 and h7 pawns.} h5 {
A brave choice! Black radically prevents g2-g4, but drastically weakens his
king.} (12... c4 {is always double-edged: White gets stability in centre, and
it makes his attack more effective.} 13. Bf5 Nf8 ({In case of} 13... g6 14. Bh3
a6 15. O-O-O b5 16. e4 dxe4 17. fxe4 {White's play in the centre is lasting
faster.}) 14. g4 Rb8 {we have been following the game Predke, A - Donchenko, A
Warsaw 2021} ({After} 14... Bxf5 15. Qxf5 g6 16. Qc2 $36 {Black has to deal
both with ..h4-h5 and g4-g5.}) {Now the simple} 15. g5 $146 Nh5 16. Kf2 {
would have put Black in a difficult situation - his knight is completely out of
play and d5 is hard to protect.}) ({The more serious possibility is} 12... a6
$5 13. g4 $146 {This consistent move is a novelty.} (13. O-O-O $6 {is dubious
because Black is first to make threats:} b5 14. g4 b4 $36 {White's king got
under strong attack in Predke, A - Petrosyan, M Warsaw 2021}) {This time Black
cannot wait - White's play with g4-g5 is coming fast.} 13... c4 14. Bf5 g6 {
This weakening move is practically forced.} 15. g5 $1 {A beginning of
interesting complications.} ({The point of Black's idea is illustrated in the
following line:} 15. Bxd7 $6 Bxd7 16. g5 $2 Nh5 17. Nxd5 Bc6 {White is
currently up a pawn, but his position is gonna be ruined very soon - Black's
bishops are too strong.}) 15... gxf5 16. gxf6 Nxf6 17. O-O-O {White needs to
join both his rooks in the attack, although his own king is unsafe.} Kh8 18.
Rhg1 b5 ({Also after} 18... Bd7 19. Rdf1 b5 20. e4 {White has full
compensation for the pawn and Black has to be very accurate. For instance,}
dxe4 21. fxe4 Nxe4 22. Bh6 $1 Bf8 {The only move.} 23. Bxf8 Rxf8 24. Nxe4 fxe4
25. Qxe4 {Black should be able to hold it according to engines, but hardly
this task will attract a human player.}) 19. e4 fxe4 20. fxe4 dxe4 21. Bg5 $44
{White has decent attacking prospects. As usual, modern engines are able to
find many defensive resources, but from a practical perspective, it looks
scary and difficult to play Black's position.}) 13. O-O-O a6 {Black signals
that he will not hesitate to act aggressively on the opposite side with ...
b7-b5,b5-b4, e.t.c} (13... Nf8 {was seen in Konyves, A - Sumets,A Vecindario
2022 In my opinion, White should have prophylactically moved his king away
from dangerous opposition on the c-file:} 14. Kb1 $146 Be6 ({After} 14... c4
15. Bf5 b5 16. g4 {White has the superior attacking prospects, although a
complex sharp struggle is ahead.}) (14... Bd7 $6 {meets} 15. Nb5 $1 Bxb5 16.
Bxb5 $16) 15. dxc5 Bxc5 16. Nf4 {White is interested in liquidating the
powerful Be6. A likely continuation would be} Rc8 17. Qb3 d4 {Now this break
isn't so dangerous.} 18. Nxe6 Nxe6 19. exd4 Nxd4 20. Qa2 $14 {White has the
advantage of the strong unopposed light-squared bishop.}) ({Worth serious
attention is} 13... cxd4 $5 14. exd4 Nb6 15. Bg5 {The pin is very annoying for
a human player but after the cool-blooded} Bd7 $1 16. Kb1 Rc8 {Black's
position seems acceptable. Still, in a practical game, I prefer White's chances
after something like} 17. Rde1 {with the intention to open the g-file with
g2-g4.}) 14. g4 {There is no way back!} hxg4 15. fxg4 Nxg4 {Black bravely
accepts a pawn!} ({Weaker is} 15... cxd4 16. exd4 Nb6 17. Bg5 Bxg4 18. Rhg1 $36
{White's initiative on the g-file overwhelms Black's extra pawn.}) 16. h5 ({
An interesting alternative is} 16. Nxd5 $5 cxd4 (16... b5 $2 {is just bad in
view of} 17. Rhg1 Nb6 18. Ba5 $18 {Lazavik,D - Kostenko,P Cheliabinsk 2022})
17. Nxd4 Nc5 {Black needs to include his queenside pieces into action as soon
as possible.} ({Possible is also} 17... Nf2 18. Rhg1 Nxd3+ 19. Qxd3 {, but
this position looks scary because White threatens 20Rxg7+, when all his pieces
are joining the attack.}) 18. Bh7+ Kh8 19. Bc3 Rxe3 $1 {It leads to wild
complications when all 3 results are possible.}) 16... Ndf6 {Black connects
his knights and strengthens g4.} ({Weaker is} 16... Nf8 $6 {So, W - Sevian, S
Saint Louis 2022} 17. Rhg1 $1 cxd4 ({White's attack is equally strong in case of
} 17... c4 18. Bf5 Nxe3 19. Bxe3 Rxe3 20. Rdf1 $40) ({Even worse is} 17... Nxe3
$2 18. Bxe3 Rxe3 19. h6 g6 20. Nxd5 $18) 18. exd4 Ne3 19. Bxe3 Rxe3 20. Nxd5
$16 {White has a free attack.}) 17. h6 Nxh6 ({After} 17... g5 18. Rhg1 Kh8 19.
Kb1 {White has superior attacking prospects. A likely continuation is} Qe7 20.
Rdf1 c4 21. Bf5 {Black's position looks vulnerable.}) 18. Rdg1 Bg4 (18... Nhg4
{is dangerous in view of} 19. Rh4 $1 c4 20. Bh7+ Kf8 21. Bf5 {Black is
practically forced to block the h-file with} Nh6 {, but after} 22. e4 $1 {
withstand the massive attack of all White's forces is a tough task for a human
player.}) 19. Kb1 $1 {A decent prophylactic move. White moves his king in
advance so as to protect him from the dangerous opposition on the c-file or
the h1-c1 diagonal. Also, White is ready to join his queen in the attack by
means of an original way.} Rc8 20. Qc1 $1 {This is the point! White's queen
isn't only eyeing h6 but can be effectively transferred to kingside through
the first rank.} Qd7 {Black connects his rooks and overprotects his bishop.} 21.
Qf1 {White does threaten to capture with his Rook on h6..} Ne4 22. Bxe4 ({
Weaker is} 22. Nxe4 dxe4 23. Bc4 cxd4 24. Rxh6 Rxc4 25. Rxd6 Qxd6 26. Rxg4 {
, and now both} dxe3 {lead to an unclear position.} ({and} 26... d3)) 22...
dxe4 23. Nd5 ({Another tempting possibility is} 23. Rxh6 $5 gxh6 24. Nd5 {
, and then Black has to find a few precise moves to stay in the game:} Be7 $1
25. Nb6 Qe6 26. Nxc8 Bg5 $1 {This calm move allows Black to nearly solve all
his problems:} ({But not} 26... Rxc8 $2 27. Nf4 Qf5 28. Qh3 $18) 27. Rxg4 Qxg4
28. Nd6 Qf3 $132) 23... Re6 {The only way to parry the threat of Rook takes on
h6, followed by Knight to f6+. After} 24. Rxg4 ({Another tempting possibility
is} 24. Nb6 Qb5 25. Nxc8 Bxe2 26. Qg2 Rg6 {, and Black holds.}) 24... Nxg4 25.
Qf5 Nh2 {The only move!} 26. Nb6 Qb5 {Once again the only move for Black!} 27.
Nxc8 Qxe2 28. Nxd6 Rxd6 {White has a draw in his pocket, but hardly more. This
long line illustrates the practical problems Black faces and therefore we
can conclude that he faces a difficult task.} *

