{[%evp 0,37,18,15,18,10,15,15,24,20,19,22,20,22,22,2,21,-14,14,0,-8,6,19,9,5,
-41,-47,-40,-47,14,12,14,35,35,35,21,22,15,72,72]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. a3 Bd6 8. Qc2 a6 {A flexible
conitnuation. Black covers the square b5 and keeps the option of playing.
c7-c5 at some point later.} 9. Nge2 Re8 {The most flexible - Black is still
ready to meet 10.f3 with c5!} ({The immediate} 9... b6 $6 {is dubious in view
of} 10. e4 $1 dxe4 11. Nxe4 {White exploits the vulnerability of the long
diagonal.} h6 (11... Nbd7 12. Nxd6 cxd6 13. Qc6 $16 {drops a pawn.}) 12. Nxd6
cxd6 13. O-O Bb7 14. Ng3 $16 {White's bishop pair seems to play an important
role, especially when his g3 Knight is heading to f5.}) 10. O-O b6 {This was
recently tested on the top level, although Black's results are unsatisfactory:
0 out of 2!} (10... Nbd7 11. b4 b6 {transposes to the text.} ({As earlier, bad
is for Black} 11... Bxh2+ $2 12. Kxh2 Ng4+ 13. Kg3 Qg5 {Santiago,Y - Sattarov,
B Chess.com INT 2023 Here the simple} 14. Bxh7+ Kf8 15. Qf5 $18 {wins on the
spot.}) (11... c6 $6 {was employed on the high level as well, but it is
illogical - now a7-a6 turns a loss of tempo.} 12. f3 a5 13. Rb1 axb4 14. axb4
Nf8 15. e4 $36 {Balck had not much to do against White's extension in centre.
Bluebaum, M - Donchenko, A Chess.com INT 2022})) (10... c5 {is insufficient for
equality:} 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Rd1 $14 {White does threaten 13.Nxd5. Pranav, A -
Harshad, S Mamaia 2022}) ({It has to be mentioned, that} 10... Bxh2+ $2 {
doesn't work in such positions. This isn't an exception:} 11. Kxh2 Ng4+ 12. Kg3
Qd6+ 13. f4 Qh6 14. Bd2 $18 {Black has absolutely nothing.}) 11. b4 Nbd7 {
This is the most precise developing move. Black doesn't need to hurry with the
fianchetto.} ({After} 11... Bb7 12. Rb1 Nbd7 13. f3 Qe7 14. Bd2 $14 {Black is
quite cramped on the queenside, and it is only a matter of time before White
will push e3-e4. Dai, C - Xu, Y Xinghua 2022}) 12. Nf4 $1 {Black is invited to
''damage'' White's pawn structure, but in return, he will be forced to exchange
his important Bishop on d6.} Bxf4 ({The alternative is} 12... Bb7 13. Rb1 Nf8
14. f3 Rb8 {The most flexible continuation. By covering the bishop Black
signals that he wants ...c7-c5.} (14... Ng6 {is well met by} 15. Nfe2 $1 {
It is better for White to keep the knights as he has more space.} Qe7 16. Ng3 {
A decent square. white isn't worried of capture on g3.} Qd7 17. Nf5 Bf8 18. Kh1
{White has the better chances in Rapport, R - Vidit, S Belgrade 2022}) 15. Nce2
$1 {This move is mainly aimed at strengthening control of c5.} Qe7 16. Bd2 Ng6 ({
Worth attention is} 16... c5 $5 17. bxc5 bxc5 18. dxc5 Bxc5 19. Nd4 {, but
also then White keeps some pressure.}) 17. Ng3 Nxf4 18. exf4 Qd7 {So far we
have seen an optimal play by both sides in Koneru, H - Zhu, J New Delhi 2023 Here I
suggest the following positional idea:} 19. Rfc1 $5 $146 {White does threaten
20.Nf5.} c6 20. Nf5 Bf8 21. a4 $14 {Black's pawn majority will be fully
neutralized after . .a4-a5, and his Bishop on b7 is very passive.}) 13. exf4 c5
{Otherwise, Black will be left with backward Pc7.} 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. Rd1 {
White has the benefit of opposition on the d-file now.} Bb7 {This was So, W -
Mamedyarov, S Bucharest 2022 Here I like the simple} 16. bxc5 $146 Nxc5 17. Be3
Nxd3 18. Qxd3 Qe7 19. Rab1 $14 {White has a slight, but long-lasting
positional advantage because of his superior bishop and his more active rooks.}
