{[%evp 0,29,19,19,27,17,1,30,19,17,19,17,25,25,27,3,23,8,17,13,22,20,26,1,5,
-27,-26,-18,-17,-17,-15,-17]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5
6. cxd5 exd5 7. a3 Bd6 8. Qc2 Na6 $5 {This unusual idea was tested in a few
top-level games, including Ding Liren - Radjabov, where the reigning world
Champion was defeated in style. Black shows his intention to open the game
with ...c7-c5.} 9. Nf3 {In most cases, White places his knight on e2 in order
to keep the possibility of building a strong pawn centre with f2-f3 and e3-e4.
However, this time White keeps the e2 square vacant for his bishop in view of .
..c7-c5-c4.} ({The above-mentioned game saw} 9. Nge2 c5 10. Bxa6 bxa6 11. dxc5
Bxc5 {The bishop pair fully compensates for Black's inferior pawn structure.}
12. b4 Bd6 13. Bb2 a5 $132 {Ding,L - Radjabov,T Madrid 2022}) 9... c6 $5 {
Curiously, this natural reply is presently untested. Since e3-e4 isn't coming
soon, Black switches to his usual manoevring plan, when his knight will head
for c7 and then for e6.} ({The alternatives are:} 9... Re8 10. O-O ({The
previosuly played} 10. b4 c6 11. Ne5 Bxe5 12. dxe5 Rxe5 13. Bb2 {led to an
interesting position, where White had sufficient compensation for the pawn due
to his strong Bishop on b2. Duda,J - Wojtaszek,R Warsaw 2023}) 10... c5 (10...
c6 {transposes to text.}) 11. Be2 $5 {A deep idea. White retreats his bishop
in advance in order to prepare for a struggle against the IQP, that will most
likely arise after he captures on c5 (or if Black chooses to capture on d4).}
Bg4 {Black activates his light-squared bishop and vacates c8 for Ra8.} ({
The ambitious} 11... c4 {might backfire in view of} 12. b3 $1 cxb3 13. Qxb3 $14
{with pressure on the Black's queenside pawns.}) ({In case of} 11... cxd4 12.
Nxd4 Nc5 {it looks like Black has decent piece play, but the strong reply} 13.
Ncb5 $1 {interrupts his plans: the exchange of the strong Bishop on d6 means
losing his attacking possibilities, while} Bf8 14. b4 Ne6 15. Bb2 $14 {allows
White to complete comfortably his development and maintain his strong pressure
on the d5 pawn.}) 12. Nb5 {Not only intending to exchange the Black bishop on
d6 but also keeping an eye on the a7 Pawn, so that Black's rook is tied up to
its defence.} Bf8 13. Bd2 {White's rooks are now connected. The White Bishop
on d2 isn't optimally developed yet, but he will certainly in the long run.}
Ne4 14. Be1 Qb6 (14... c4 15. b3 cxb3 16. Qxb3 {is better for White, as
earlier.}) 15. Nc3 {The White knight completed his job and now comes back in
order to be exchanged with the active Black Knight on e4.} Rad8 16. dxc5 Naxc5
17. Rd1 {Black must claim compensation for his weak IQP. The exchange of
Knights on c3 will significantly help White to activate most of his forces.}) (
9... c5 10. O-O c4 {This pawn structure is statically good for Black, but if
he cannot connect his pawns with the move ...b7-b5 it is a different story.}
11. Be2 Nc7 12. a4 {An essential move - White has to prevent the ''squeezing'' .
..b7-b5-b4.} Bg4 ({Somewhat artificial is} 12... Na6 13. b3 Nb4 14. Qb1 cxb3
15. Qxb3 {The Black Knight on b4 is nicely placed, but it doesn't provide full
compensation for Black's structural weaknesses.} a5 16. Ba3 Bf5 17. Rac1 $14 {
White has the better prospects because of the excellent b5-outpost and superior
pawn structure. Garriga Cazorla,P - Bilych,O Escaldes 2022}) 13. b3 Rc8 14.
bxc4 dxc4 {This position occurred in Rakhmanov, A - Remizov, Y Obninsk 2022 White
should have played:} 15. h3 $146 Bh5 16. Ne5 $1 {White exploits the lack of
piece coordination in Black's camp to increase the pressure on c4.} Bxe2 17.
Qxe2 {Now the Black Pawn on c4 is attacked with two different White pieces..}
Ncd5 18. Nxd5 Bxe5 19. Nc3 Bd6 20. Ba3 $14 {Black was able to maintain the
material balance, but White is clearly better because the c4 Pawn is very
vulnerable, and Black will have to face .. e3-e4 soon.}) 10. O-O Re8 (10... Nc7
{is well met by} 11. Ne5 $1 c5 12. f4 {The strong Ne5 offers White good
chances in the upcoming strategic struggle. The most challenging reaction here
is} c4 (12... Ne6 13. Qf2 b6 14. Kh1 Bb7 15. Bd2 {leads to a long struggle,
where I prefer White's chances from a practical point of view. A likely
continuation could be:} cxd4 16. exd4 Ne4 17. Nxe4 dxe4 18. Bc4 {with
an interesting play on the kingside starting with the moves f4-f5-f6.}) 13. Be2
b5 14. b3 $1 {White exploits opponent's lack of development and prevents his
further expansion with ...a7-a5, b5-b4, e.t.c} Bb7 15. Rb1 Rb8 16. bxc4 bxc4
17. Bd2 $14 {The Black Pawn on c4 is comfortably blocked, and now White can
switch to his attacking plans on the kingside starting with Bd2-e1-h4.}) 11.
b4 {Not only preparing to fianchetto his Bishop, but also declaring his
intention to expand with ..b4-b5 at some point.} Nc7 12. Ne5 $5 {White offers
an interesting pawn sacrifice.} ({The routine} 12. b5 cxb5 13. Nxb5 Nxb5 14.
Bxb5 Bd7 {offers no advantage.}) 12... Bxe5 {Otherwise after ..f2-f4 Black's
kingside will be rather cramped.} 13. dxe5 Rxe5 14. Bb2 Re8 15. Ne2 $44 {
White has full compensation for the pawn due to strong unopposed dark-squared
bishop and his good piece coordination.} *

